[k][j]; // Update to reflect correct predecessor } } } } } } \`\`\` # Correcting \`getShortestPath\` Next, correct the \`getShortestPath\` method to prevent potential infinite loops. To stop an infinite loop, we will validate the next step, and if no progress can be made (e.g., because \`-1\` is encountered or we are about to append a node we have already appended), we break the loop and log an error if necessary. # Updated \`getShortestPath\` Method \`\`\`java private static String getShortestPath(int source, int dest) { if (adjMatrix[source][dest] == Integer.MAX_VALUE) { return \\"No path\\"; } StringBuilder path = new StringBuilder(\\"V\\" + (source + 1)); int next = pMatrix[source][dest]; // Introduce a set to track visited nodes to prevent revisiting Set<Integer> visited = new HashSet<>(); while (next != dest) { // Break if we encounter -1 or a cycle if(next == -1 || !visited.add(next)) { path.append(\\" -> No valid continuation\\"); break; } path.append(\\" -> V\\").append(next + 1); next = pMatrix[next][dest]; } // Ensure to append destination if we have a valid path if (next != -1) { path.append(\\" -> V\\").append(dest + 1); } return path.toString(); } \`\`\` This improved version adds checks to prevent cycling through already visited nodes, thus preventing an infinite loop caused by incorrect \`pMatrix\` updates or cycles within the graph itself. Additionally, the update to \`calculateShortestPaths\` ensures that \`pMatrix\` is filled correctly, reflecting the immediate predecessor node on the shortest path correctly. With these insights and adjustments, your Floyd-Warshall implementation should be more robust, specifically in handling path reconstruction without running into infinite loops or memory issues."},{"prompt":"import java.io.*; import java.util.Scanner; public class floyd { private static int[][] adjMatrix; private static int[][] pMatrix; private static final String OUTPUT_FILE = \\"output.txt\\"; public static void main(String[] args) throws IO